          "Being “at-risk” (1) vs not “at-risk” (0)",
          "2468 students",
          "Undergraduate Pograms in an Aulstralian University",
          "Enrollment Data, LMS logs",
          "[Gender, SAS_ADD_CURRENT_SHORT_SAS, AGE_NUM, ATTENDANCE_TYPE_DESC, ATTENDANCE_MODE_SHORT_DESC, AUST_SES, APPL_WAS_FIRST_PREF, IN_MULTI_PROG_ANY_YR, iN_MULT_PROG_THIS_YR, pARENT_1_EDUCATION_CIODE, pARENT_2_EDUCATION_CODE, HIGH_SCHOOL_STATE, ATAR_rank, BOOK_VIEW, CHOICE_VIEW, COURSE_VISIT, FORUM_ADD_DISCUSSION, FORUM_ADD_POST, FORUM_VIEW_DISCUSSION, fORUM_VIEW_FORUM, lESSON_VIEW, OUWIKI_EDIT, OUWIKI_VIEW, QUIZ_ATTEMPT, QUIZ_REVIEW, QUIZ_VIEW, RESOURCE_VIEW]",
          "End of Course",
          "Discretization happens across different numeric variables and categorized according to the 4 quartiles. \n\nSince the study includes a general model and multiple sub-models that account for different student subgroups, each student enrollment is included in total in 8 distinct datasets. \n\nThen, females and males are subsequently separated in 6 additional datasets.",
          "Naive Bayes, SMO, J48, JRip",
          "10-Fold Cross-Validation",
          "{Accuracy: 0.798 - J48, Precision: 0.682 - NB, Recall: 0.374 - NB, F1-Score: 0.48 - NB, Cohen’s Kappa: 0.43 - NB, AUC: 0.699 - J48}",
          "Authors create a base, course-agnostic model athat also does not consider student sub-groups and, later, compares the performance of this base model against different models created specifically for different sub-groups. \n\nSub-models seem to outperform ther base model in general, but there is no specific submodel that always outperforms the others.\n\nAlso, combining data from different sources - enrollment + logs seems to improve performance of the models.\n\nResults shown only refer to base models.",
          "Data only refers to a set of domestic students in a very specific department.\n\nAdditional categorization of the LMS data would also be benefical.\n\nNo early prediction"
        ]
      ],
      "index": 5
    }
